"ItemDescMemoryOfMage"                     = "In the kingdom, the legendary mage’s name is not spoken aloud in haste. He was inscribed in the Book of Royal Archmages not with gold ink, but with black — the mark of those who gave their lives, leaving behind no school, disciples, or heirs, to save the world itself.\n\nIn the mage towers, students begin their training with the same legend. They are told of the Protector without followers — a mage who founded no order, wrote no treatises, and sought no recognition, but in his hour of need stood between the living and death.\n\nBefore difficult spells, young mages place their hand momentarily on the cold stone of the wall and whisper his name — not as a prayer, but as a reminder: true magic serves not glory, but choice.";
"ItemDescMemoryOfWarrior"                  = "The legendary warrior’s sacrifice is spoken of simply in the kingdom, without lofty words.\n\nHis sword was returned to its source — the family crypt — and it wasn’t the priests or military leaders who insisted on this, but the common people.\n\nPeasants, merchants, and artisans leave small tokens of gratitude at the crypt entrance: a broken horseshoe, a piece of leather, a bundle of grain. No one calls it a tradition — it’s simply done when they remember.\nThey say he fought not for victory, but so that others would have time to escape, and therefore his sword shouldn’t be visible — it should rest.\n\nSometimes, on rainy days, a lantern is lit near the crypt. Not in honor of the hero, but so that the path home will always be illuminated, even if you never return.";
"ItemDescMemoryOfBard"                     = "The memory of the legendary bard lives in the kingdom not in stone or in books, but in voices.\nHis song has long since lost its words — everyone sings it in their own way, humming only fragments of a melody that cannot be captured in its entirety. But that’s how it’s passed on: not precisely, but vividly.\n\nChildren hum it as they play on the thresholds of houses, unaware of its origin. Travelers quietly pick it up on the road when the evening grows too long. No one calls it the memory of a hero — it’s simply a song that comes to them.\n\nAnd on clear nights, when the moon hangs low, some swear the wind suddenly begins to sound smoother and warmer. And if you listen closely, it seems as if someone is singing nearby — not for glory or reward, but so that the road doesn’t seem empty.";
"ItemDescMemoryOfSmith"                    = "The memory of the legendary blacksmith doesn’t resound loudly in the kingdom — it weighs heavily.\nHis hammer was returned to the forge of his hometown and hung by the hearth where he once worked. It’s no longer used to forge weapons, but it’s never removed: the fire in that forge has never gone out for a single night since.\n\nA monument was erected at the capital’s gates — a stone anvil, crude and simple. It bears no names or inscriptions: everyone knows to whom it’s dedicated. On the opening day, the dwarves of the Ash Caves stood in a circle and silently struck the ground with their hammers. No songs, no speeches — only a dull, heavy sound that shook the stones.\n\nSince then, they say: if the city gates suddenly become quieter than usual, it means someone has stopped at the anvil and remembered the one who once stayed so others could leave.";
"ItemDescCurseOfMage"                      = "Few know that the mage’s curse began in the Misty Gorge. One of the illusions, not completely dispelled, touched his face — and from then on, half of his features seemed to have a life of their own: reflected in glass incorrectly, whispering other people’s thoughts, remembering things that never happened.\n\nOver time, madness slowly began to consume him from within. Spells became increasingly difficult, sleep brought only fog, and his own reflection inspired fear. He tried to fight, sought healing, but realized that some distortions could not be reversed.\n\nOne day, he left alone, leaving no farewells. He was last seen at the edge of the Misty Gorge, where illusions never completely dissipate.\nThey say that now, among the shadows, one can discern a figure with a half-familiar face — it does not attack or call, only stares, as if still trying to remember who it was.";
"ItemDescCurseOfWarrior"                   = "The warrior’s curse was born not of magic, but of a choice denied.\nAt Stone Pass, he was prevented from confronting the giant — and this decision, made out of caution, left a rift deeper than any wound.\n\nHonor, unrequited, began to rot. He left alone, without words or witnesses, to reclaim what he considered rightfully his.\n\nBut when he returned to the pass, he was already broken: doubt dulled his hand, fatigue weighed his steps, and rage proved weaker than stone.\n\nHe didn’t last five minutes.\n\nNow the giant wears his cloak, draped over his shoulder like a warm cloth. He doesn’t know it’s a trophy, doesn’t understand its significance — and in this final humiliation, the warrior’s honor dissolved completely, becoming nothing more than the wind on the pass.";
"ItemDescCurseOfBard"                      = "The bard’s curse began in the Forest of Singing Winds, where he once dared to respond to the songs of the dryads. They managed to break through further, but the forest did not completely release him — part of the melody wove itself into his voice, leaving an alien rhythm within him.\n\nOver time, the songs ceased to be quiet. They came in his dreams, interrupted his thoughts, compelled him to sing even when he was silent. His music became strange: it contained a melancholy that made the listeners’ hearts clench, and a call that made them want to go — not knowing where.\n\nHe resisted to the last, but one day he realized he could no longer distinguish his own desires from those whispered by the forest. On a windless night, he left his house and walked into the thicket, following the voices that now sounded like a sentence.\n\nSince then, a wordless song is sometimes heard in the Forest of Singing Winds — uneven, broken. And those who recognize the human voice in it try to leave quickly: they say the forest sings through the one who once tried to answer it.";
"ItemDescCurseOfSmith"                     = "The blacksmith’s curse began in the Ash Caves, when he found red crystals, warm as life, amid the slag and rusty machinery. He mistook them for a rare ore and began studying them, testing their sound and impact, without noticing how they began to respond to him.\n\nAt first, the crystals merely drove him mad — distorting time, making him hear meaningful words in the grinding of gears. Then they sprouted: scarlet veins appeared beneath his skin, his bones grew heavier, his movements slower but stronger.\n\nWhen he realized he could no longer distinguish his own will from the call of the earth, it was too late. He removed his hammer, left it at the entrance, and went deeper into the caves, where fire and stone never sleep.\nThey say that now in the Ash Caves, a mechanism that no one has ever set in motion sometimes moves, and in its rhythm one can hear the heavy breathing of one who has chosen to merge with the earth forever.";
"ItemDescStarSupernova"                    = "Night wrapped the village in thick velvet, and only a few fading window lights dared to rival the stars. The sky hung low and silent, as if holding its breath.\n\nAnd then one of the stars flared.\n\nAt first, it was no more than a spark lost among the silver scatter of lights. Then its radiance began to swell with unnatural force, as though a fiery rift had opened in the very heart of the heavens. In a single instant, the darkness recoiled: rooftops blazed with cold brilliance, the well’s wooden beam flashed like steel, and sharp black shadows slashed across the earth.\n\nIt was not merely light — it was the cry of a dying sun, forged into a blinding crown of fire. The sky blossomed in orange flame, and for a fleeting moment it seemed that eternity itself had looked down upon the quiet village.";
"ItemDescClotOfMagic"                      = "It hovered in the air, touching neither earth nor wind — a cluster of pure magic, radiating a soft yet unbearably deep light. Its surface flowed like living quicksilver, shimmering in shades of azure, gold, and a faint violet flame. Within it, tiny sparks flared and faded, as though stars were being born and extinguished in a sky too small for infinity.\n\nA quiet hum emanated from it, like the echo of a distant choir chanting ancient words long forgotten. The air around it thickened and trembled, grass bent low, and shadows stretched toward it as if drawn to a source of life. To come near was to feel your skin prickle, as though the very fabric of the world brushed against you with unseen fingers.";
"ItemDescSpaceship"                        = "It towered above the village like a steel giant strayed from another world. Its matte-silver hull, traced with seams, resembled the armor of an ancient titan, while the rounded cockpit with its dark glass dome gleamed like an enchanted eye. Within its belly, an unseen force hummed softly — like a captive star bound obediently within iron ribs.\n\nMassive supports, like the legs of a colossal guardian, pierced the earth, leaving faintly smoking marks in the grass from its recent landing. Along its sides protruded cylinders and structures — perhaps vessels of arcane ether, perhaps the organs of some mechanical beast unknown to humankind. Amber lights flickered beneath its hull, like the breathing of a dragon fallen asleep among fields and windmills.\n\nAgainst the backdrop of blue mountains and a tranquil sky, it seemed a messenger from distant constellations — a wanderer descending into a realm of thatched roofs and pastoral calm. In its silhouette lingered ancient power and silent mystery, as though it carried legends of worlds where the heavens are roads and the stars serve as lanterns for travelers.";
"ItemDescSupernovaInSpace"                 = "At the heart of the abyssal darkness, a star reached the limit of its nuclear endurance. Its core, compressed to an almost impossible density, collapsed in an instant and then unleashed energy rivaling the luminosity of an entire galaxy. The flash tore through the cosmic night — an overwhelming surge of gamma and X-ray radiation ripping through space as if the very fabric of reality had fractured.\n\nThe shockwave, expanding at thousands of kilometers per second, hurled layers of incandescent plasma into the vacuum. Swirling currents of ionized gas formed a radiant ring — the advancing front of matter enriched with heavy elements forged in the star’s final fractions of a second. Within this blazing cloud, gold, uranium, and other rare atoms were synthesized — the raw material for future planets and civilizations.\nAs the brilliance slowly began to fade, a сверхdense remnant remained behind — a neutron star or a nascent black hole. Space around it warped under extreme gravity, and for eons the surrounding galaxy would carry the echo of the catastrophe. It was not merely an explosion, it was a cosmic act of matter recycling, rewriting the chemical map of the Universe.";
"ItemDescAlienEgg"                         = "Transparent cylindrical capsule with metallic end caps. The glass body reveals its contents — inside, a bright orange-golden substance pulses, emitting a soft glow. The light reflects off the inner walls of the capsule, creating a sense of warmth and contained energy.\n\nInside the capsule is something resembling an alien organism. It looks like a living lava: a dome-shaped form rises at the center, with wave-like flows spreading outward, as if the liquid is in constant motion. Tiny sparkling points are visible throughout the mass, like microscopic flashes of energy.\n\nThe organism appears active and almost intelligent — its surface shimmers and seems to respond to its surroundings.";
"ItemDescAbilityNecromancy"                = "Necromancy is not merely the magic of death — it is a brazen defiance of time itself and the laws of the universe. A true master does not brandish a staff wildly but conducts a faint, whispered dialogue with the void, feeling for the thin threads of fading souls within the frozen haze of the Veil. To them, flesh is but clay and bone a mere framework, waiting to be imbued with a semblance of life by pouring ethereal energy — heavy as quicksilver — into cold, stagnant veins.\n\nIn the eyes of a necromant, the world is drained of color but teeming with shadows and echoes. Mastery is measured by sheer will: should one show a flicker of weakness or fear, the risen dead—driven only by hunger and residual malice — will turn their skeletal fingers upon their creator. The highest manifestation of power is not the raising of rotting hordes, but the ability to command an ancient wraith to divulge secrets of forgotten eras with a mere whisper, all while clinging to one’s own fading humanity.\n\nThe price of such dominion is always etched upon the mage’s visage: pallid skin, frost clinging to the fingertips, and a gaze fixed upon the infinite «nothing». Where an ordinary person sees only an end and decay, the master of necromancy sees an unfinished symbiosis, where death becomes just another stage of service. It is a path of solitude and eternal chill, where the only faithful companions are those who can no longer betray — for they are already dead.";
"ItemDescAbilityMeditation"                = "Mastery of meditation is not merely a silencing of the mind, but the art of taming an internal storm. While the common man drowns in the chaos of his own thoughts, the true practitioner erects an impregnable citadel within the halls of the soul. With every deep breath, the boundaries of the self expand, blurring the line between flesh and ether, until the heartbeat synchronizes with the very rhythm of the earth.\n\nAt the peak of concentration, the world freezes like a fly trapped in honeyed amber. The master perceives mana flows invisible to the common eye, drifting through space, and senses the vibrations of others’ intentions long before they take shape. In this state of absolute stillness, the mind becomes like the mirrored surface of a mountain lake: it reflects the truth without distortion, remaining motionless even if a stone of rage or a blade of doubt is cast into its depths.\n\nThe highest tier of this art allows one to draw power from the Void itself. Shrouded in an aura of serenity, the meditator becomes an unshakeable pillar of existence, capable of mending wounds of spirit and body through sheer force of will. For such a master, time transforms into an obedient river and silence into a formidable weapon, for she who has fathomed her own depths gains dominion over reality without lifting a finger.";

