/* Random facts about pets */
"FactDog1"                                 = "A dog’s nose print is as unique as a human fingerprint. It can be used by forensic investigators to identify specific animals.";
"FactDog2"                                 = "Dogs have three eyelids in each eye. The third lid, called the nictitating membrane, helps keep the eye lubricated and protected.";
"FactDog3"                                 = "Bloodhounds have a sense of smell so accurate that it is admissible as evidence in a court of law. They can follow tracks that are over 300 hours old.";
"FactDog4"                                 = "Your dog’s sense of smell is roughly 10,000 to 100,000 times more acute than yours. If you can smell a teaspoon of sugar in your coffee, they can smell a teaspoon of sugar in an Olympic-sized swimming pool.";
"FactDog5"                                 = "Dogs have about 1,700 taste buds, while humans have around 9,000. This is why they are often more interested in how food smells than how it actually tastes.";
"FactDog6"                                 = "A dog’s whiskers are packed with nerves that send sensory information to the brain. These «vibrissae» help them detect subtle changes in air currents and navigate in the dark.";
"FactDog7"                                 = "Puppies are born deaf and blind. Their ear canals and eyes don’t fully open until they are about two weeks old.";
"FactDog8"                                 = "Dogs can hear frequencies up to 45,000 Hz, whereas humans only hear up to 20,000 Hz. This allows them to hear the high-pitched «hum» of electronics that we can’t perceive.";
"FactDog9"                                 = "Basenjis are the only breed of dog that cannot bark. Instead, they make a sound known as a «barroo», which sounds like a strange yodel.";
"FactDog10"                                = "Some dogs are «left-pawed» while others are «right-pawed». You can test this by seeing which paw they use first when trying to get a treat out of a toy.";
"FactDog11"                                = "Dogs sweat only through their paw pads. To cool down the rest of their body, they rely on panting to evaporate moisture from their tongues.";
"FactDog12"                                = "A dog’s ear is controlled by at least 18 different muscles. These muscles allow them to tilt and rotate their ears independently to pinpoint the source of a sound.";
"FactDog13"                                = "Newfoundland dogs have webbed feet and a water-resistant coat. This makes them world-class swimmers who were originally bred to help fishermen.";
"FactDog14"                                = "The Chow Chow and the Shar-Pei are the only two dog breeds that have completely black or blue tongues. Scientists aren’t entirely sure why this genetic trait exists.";
"FactDog15"                                = "Dogs can see in the dark thanks to a special membrane called the tapetum lucidum. This layer reflects light back through the retina, which also causes their eyes to glow in photos.";
"FactDog16"                                = "A dog’s shoulder blades are not attached to the rest of its skeleton. This «floating» design allows for greater flexibility and a longer stride when running.";
"FactDog17"                                = "The Lundehund is a breed with six toes on each foot. This physical anomaly helped them climb slippery cliffs in Norway to hunt puffins.";
"FactDog18"                                = "Small dogs generally live longer than large dogs. A giant breed like a Great Dane has a much faster metabolic rate, which contributes to quicker aging.";
"FactDog19"                                = "Dogs have a «nephrophilic» attraction to the smell of rotting things. They roll in stinky messes to mask their own scent, a behavior inherited from their wolf ancestors.";
"FactDog20"                                = "The average dog’s mouth exerts about 320 pounds of pressure per square inch. Some breeds, like the Mastiff, can exert over 500 pounds of pressure.";
"FactDog21"                                = "When a dog spins in circles before lying down, they are following an ancient instinct. Their ancestors did this to flatten tall grass and scuffle away any snakes or insects.";
"FactDog22"                                = "Dogs kick their back legs after pooping to spread their scent. They have scent glands in their paws that leave an «olfactory business card» for other dogs.";
