"FactDragon100"                            = "Despite their fearsome reputation, many modern stories depict dragons as the ultimate protectors of the natural world.";
"FactAlien1"                               = "The Fermi Paradox highlights the contradiction between the high probability of alien life and our lack of contact. It asks the simple, haunting question: «Where is everybody?»";
"FactAlien2"                               = "Some scientists suggest the «Zoo Hypothesis» as an answer to this paradox. It proposes that advanced aliens are aware of us but choose to watch from a distance without interfering.";
"FactAlien3"                               = "The «Great Filter» theory suggests there is a developmental wall that most civilizations hit before they can travel through space. This could mean we are either incredibly lucky to have passed it or doomed to face it soon.";
"FactAlien4"                               = "Frank Drake created the Drake Equation in 1961 to estimate the number of active civilizations in our galaxy. While mathematically sound, many of its variables remain complete guesswork.";
"FactAlien5"                               = "The «Wow! Signal» was a strong narrowband radio signal detected in 1977 that lasted 72 seconds. It has never been heard again, leaving its origin one of the greatest mysteries in SETI history.";
"FactAlien6"                               = "The Rare Earth Hypothesis argues that the conditions required for complex life are so specific they might only exist here. This suggests that while microbial life might be common, «intelligent» life is a cosmic fluke.";
"FactAlien7"                               = "Some researchers believe in «Shadow Biospheres» right here on Earth. These would be life forms with a completely different biochemistry that we simply haven’t learned how to see yet.";
"FactAlien8"                               = "The «Dark Forest» theory posits that the universe is a dangerous place where civilizations stay silent to avoid being destroyed. Under this view, any civilization that broadcasts its location is a target.";
"FactAlien9"                               = "NASA’s Viking landers in 1976 actually tested Martian soil for life and got a positive result. However, the scientific community later dismissed it as a non-biological chemical reaction.";
"FactAlien10"                              = "The Panspermia theory suggests that life on Earth may have been «seeded» by microbes hitching a ride on asteroids. If true, we might actually be the descendants of Martians or other aliens.";
"FactAlien11"                              = "Tardigrades, or «water bears», can survive the vacuum and intense radiation of open space. Their resilience proves that Earth-based life could potentially survive a journey between planets.";
"FactAlien12"                              = "The bacterium Deinococcus radiodurans can survive radiation doses thousands of times higher than what would kill a human. It is often nicknamed «Conan the Bacterium» for its incredible toughness.";
"FactAlien13"                              = "On Saturn’s moon Enceladus, giant geysers blast saltwater and organic molecules into space. This suggests a warm, subsurface ocean that might be the best place to look for life today.";
"FactAlien14"                              = "Jupiter’s moon Europa contains more liquid water than all of Earth’s oceans combined. This water is hidden beneath a global shell of ice that may be miles thick.";
"FactAlien15"                              = "Titan, a moon of Saturn, has lakes and rivers made of liquid methane and ethane instead of water. Life there would need a completely different «methanogenic» biochemistry to survive.";
"FactAlien16"                              = "Some scientists believe Venus could host microbial life in its upper atmosphere. While the surface is a 460°C hellscape, the clouds 50 kilometers up have Earth-like temperatures and pressures.";
"FactAlien17"                              = "Deep-sea hydrothermal vents on Earth host life that survives without any sunlight at all. These ecosystems serve as a primary model for how life might exist on icy moons like Europa.";
"FactAlien18"                              = "Microbes have been found living inside solid rocks deep within the Earth’s crust. This «deep biosphere» suggests life could exist deep underground on Mars where it is protected from radiation.";
"FactAlien19"                              = "There is a «habitable zone» not just around stars, but around entire galaxies. Too close to the center and radiation is too high, too far out and there aren’t enough heavy elements to build planets.";
"FactAlien20"                              = "Red Dwarf stars are the most common in the universe and can live for trillions of years. This gives life on their planets a massive amount of time to evolve, though these stars are prone to violent flares.";
"FactAlien21"                              = "The exoplanet HD 189733b looks like a beautiful blue marble, but it rains molten glass sideways. Winds on this planet reach speeds of 8,700 kilometers per hour.";
"FactAlien22"                              = "55 Cancri e is a «Super-Earth» that is believed to be made largely of diamond. The planet is so hot and under such pressure that its carbon-rich interior has likely crystallized.";
"FactAlien23"                              = "TrES-2b is the darkest planet ever discovered, reflecting less than 1% of the light that hits it. It is literally blacker than coal and glows with a faint, hellish red heat.";
"FactAlien24"                              = "The planet K2-18b was found to have water vapor in its atmosphere and sits in its star’s habitable zone. It is one of the top candidates for a «Hycean» world—a planet covered entirely by a massive ocean.";
"FactAlien25"                              = "WASP-12b is a «pitch black» planet that is currently being eaten by its host star. It is being stretched into an egg shape by the star’s gravity and will be consumed in about 10 million years.";
"FactAlien26"                              = "On the planet WASP-76b, it is so hot that iron vaporizes during the day and falls as «iron rain» at night. The temperature difference between its two sides is over 1,000°C.";
"FactAlien27"                              = "Kepler-16b is a real-life «Tatooine» that orbits two stars at once. If you stood on its surface, you would have two distinct shadows and see two sunsets every day.";
"FactAlien28"                              = "Gliese 581c was once thought to be a prime candidate for life, but it is tidally locked. One side is a frozen wasteland while the other is a scorched desert, leaving only a thin «twilight» strip potentially habitable.";
"FactAlien29"                              = "J1407b is an exoplanet with a ring system 200 times larger than Saturn’s. If it replaced Saturn in our solar system, its rings would be clearly visible and larger than the full moon.";
"FactAlien30"                              = "The «Methuselah» planet, PSR B1620-26 b, is nearly 13 billion years old. It formed only a billion years after the Big Bang, suggesting planets (and life) could have started very early.";
"FactAlien31"                              = "In 1974, we broadcast the Arecibo Message toward a star cluster 25,000 light-years away. It contained binary code describing human DNA, our appearance, and our solar system.";
"FactAlien32"                              = "The Voyager Golden Records contain sounds of Earth, music, and greetings in 55 languages. They are currently the most distant man-made objects, acting as a «message in a bottle» to the cosmos.";
"FactAlien33"                              = "Technosignatures are signs of advanced technology, like atmospheric pollution or massive solar arrays. Some astronomers look for «CFCs» in alien atmospheres as proof of industrial civilizations.";
"FactAlien34"                              = "A Dyson Sphere is a theoretical megastructure built around a star to capture all of its energy. If we saw a star’s light dipping in a strange, non-periodic way, it might be evidence of such a structure.";
"FactAlien35"                              = "Tabby’s Star (KIC 8462852) gained fame for its erratic dimming that defied standard explanations. While most now think it’s dust, some still speculate it could be an alien construction project.";
"FactAlien36"                              = "We have sent «Active SETI» messages to nearby stars, but many scientists think this is dangerous. Stephen Hawking famously warned that we should be careful about shouting into the cosmic woods.";
"FactAlien37"                              = "Laser SETI looks for brief pulses of light rather than radio waves. Advanced aliens might use lasers for communication because they can carry much more data over long distances.";
"FactAlien38"                              = "Some theorists suggest that Fast Radio Bursts (FRBs) could be the exhaust from alien spacecraft. These millisecond-long bursts of energy come from galaxies billions of light-years away.";
"FactAlien39"                              = "The «Oort Cloud» at the edge of our solar system could contain trillions of icy bodies. Some speculate that alien probes could be hiding there, waiting for us to become «interesting» enough.";
"FactAlien40"                              = "If an alien civilization 65 million light-years away looked at Earth through a powerful telescope, they would see dinosaurs. Light takes time to travel, making the universe a giant time machine.";
"FactAlien41"                              = "Life on Earth uses Left-Handed Amino Acids, a phenomenon called homochirality. If we find life that uses right-handed ones, it would prove a completely independent origin of life.";
"FactAlien42"                              = "Arsenic-based life was once thought to have been found in a California lake. While the study was later debunked, it opened the door to the idea of life using «toxic» elements.";
"FactAlien43"                              = "Silicon-based life is a popular sci-fi trope because silicon is chemically similar to carbon. However, silicon is much «stickier» and harder to breathe out as a gas, making it less likely than carbon.";
"FactAlien44"                              = "Bioluminescence might be a common trait for life on planets with low light or deep oceans. Entire alien ecosystems could glow in the dark to communicate or hunt.";
"FactAlien45"                              = "High-gravity planets might produce «flat» life forms that hug the ground to avoid being crushed. These creatures would likely be incredibly muscular and slow-moving.";
"FactAlien46"                              = "Planets orbiting M-dwarf stars (red dwarfs) are often bathed in infrared light. Plants there might appear black to our eyes to absorb as much energy as possible.";
"FactAlien47"                              = "The discovery of Phosphine in the clouds of Venus sparked a massive debate in 2020. On Earth, this gas is mostly produced by anaerobic microbes, making it a «potential» biosignature.";
"FactAlien48"                              = "Scientists have found amino acids—the building blocks of proteins—on meteorites like the Murchison meteorite. This proves that the ingredients for life are literally floating around in space.";
"FactAlien49"                              = "«Oumuamua», the first interstellar object detected passing through our solar system, had a very strange shape and acceleration. While most think it’s a comet, Harvard’s Avi Loeb famously argued it could be a light sail.";
"FactAlien50"                              = "If life exists on a rogue planet (a planet with no star), it would have to survive on internal geothermal heat. Such life would live in permanent darkness, likely deep under a thick crust of ice.";
"FactAlien51"                              = "On HAT-P-7b, the clouds are likely made of corundum—the mineral that forms rubies and sapphires. This means the planet literally has «precious gem» weather.";
"FactAlien52"                              = "Kepler-10b is a «lava world» where the surface is so hot it stays molten. One side of the planet is a permanent ocean of liquid rock.";
"FactAlien53"                              = "Some planets are «Eyeball Planets», where tidal locking creates a giant circle of liquid water facing the star. From space, these planets look like a giant eye staring into the void.";
"FactAlien54"                              = "Gliese 436b is a planet made of «burning ice». The gravity is so strong it keeps water in a solid state (Ice VII) even though the temperature is over 400°C.";
"FactAlien55"                              = "PSR J1719-1438 b is a planet that orbits a pulsar and is almost entirely made of diamond. It is essentially the compressed remains of a former star’s core.";
"FactAlien56"                              = "The planet HD 209458b (Osiris) is evaporating so fast it has a tail like a comet. It is losing about 10,000 tons of hydrogen every single second.";
"FactAlien57"                              = "TOI-849b appears to be the exposed core of a gas giant whose atmosphere was stripped away. It is a rocky world 40 times the mass of Earth, which shouldn’t technically be possible.";
"FactAlien58"                              = "Some planets orbit three stars at once, like the system GW Orionis. The gravitational dance in these systems is so complex it can tear planetary disks apart.";
"FactAlien59"                              = "Kepler-444 is a star system that is 11 billion years old and has five Earth-sized planets. This proves that rocky planets have been forming since the universe was in its infancy.";
"FactAlien60"                              = "The «Pink Planet» GJ 504b glows with a magenta hue because it is still young and hot. It is roughly the size of Jupiter but four times more massive.";
"FactAlien61"                              = "The first human «message» to potentially reach aliens was actually a 1936 TV broadcast of the Berlin Olympics. It wasn’t intended for space, but the signal was strong enough to leak out.";
"FactAlien62"                              = "NASA has a Planetary Protection Officer whose job is to prevent Earth microbes from «infecting» other planets. They also ensure we don’t accidentally bring alien «bugs» back to Earth.";
"FactAlien63"                              = "If we ever find a signal, the SETI post-detection protocols say we shouldn’t reply without international consultation. Of course, there is no way to actually enforce this «rule».";
"FactAlien64"                              = "Some philosophers argue that finding aliens would be the most humbling event in human history. It would officially end the idea that we are the center of the universe.";
"FactAlien65"                              = "The «Lincos» language was created by Hans Freudenthal as a way to communicate with aliens using logic and math. It is designed to be understood by any civilization with a basic grasp of numbers.";
"FactAlien66"                              = "In 2008, the song «Across the Universe» by the Beatles was beamed toward the North Star, Polaris. It will take 431 years for the «message» to arrive.";
"FactAlien67"                              = "Some scientists think we should look for «Alien Trash» rather than signals. Dyson spheres, spent nuclear fuel, or defunct probes might be easier to spot than a deliberate greeting.";
"FactAlien68"                              = "The METI (Messaging Extraterrestrial Intelligence) organization actively sends signals to the stars. This is controversial because it «advertises» our presence to unknown entities.";
"FactAlien69"                              = "Frank Drake once sent a «picture» of a human to a colleague to see if he could decode it. The colleague failed, highlighting how hard it will be to understand an alien message.";
"FactAlien70"                              = "Astronomer Jill Tarter has spent over 35 years searching for signals. She was the primary inspiration for Jodie Foster’s character in the movie Contact.";
"FactAlien71"                              = "If a planet has a very thick atmosphere, life might evolve to float like biological hot-air balloons. These «air-whales» could spend their entire lives without ever touching a surface.";
"FactAlien72"                              = "Life on a high-gravity world would likely have many legs or a very wide base. Think of creatures built like tanks or low-slung crabs.";
"FactAlien73"                              = "On planets orbiting binary stars, life would have to adapt to wildly changing light cycles. Some «days» might have two suns, while others might have only one or none.";
"FactAlien74"                              = "Some speculate that «intelligent» life might eventually move beyond biology into digital forms. A civilization millions of years older than us might just be a giant supercomputer.";
"FactAlien75"                              = "If aliens evolved in the subsurface oceans of moons, they might not even know stars exist. They would live in a world of ice and water, unaware of the vast universe above.";
"FactAlien76"                              = "Convergent evolution suggests that similar environments produce similar features. This means aliens might have eyes, limbs, or brains remarkably like ours if their planet is Earth-like.";
"FactAlien77"                              = "Aliens might not use sound to communicate if their atmosphere is too thin. They might use light-flashes, scent-trails, or even direct electrical signals.";
"FactAlien78"                              = "Large-brained animals on Earth, like octopuses and crows, show that intelligence can evolve in very different body types. Alien «geniuses» don’t necessarily need to look like humans.";
"FactAlien79"                              = "If a planet is cloud-covered 24/7, the inhabitants might never develop astronomy. Their technology and culture would be fundamentally limited by their lack of «the big picture».";
"FactAlien80"                              = "Some scientists think the «standard» alien might be small, microbial, and incredibly boring. We hope for «Little Green Men», but we’ll likely find «Little Green Slime».";
"FactAlien81"                              = "«Polyextremophiles» are organisms that can survive multiple harsh conditions at once. They are the ultimate «survivors» and the best candidates for interstellar travel.";
"FactAlien82"                              = "The «Water Hole» is a specific frequency range in the radio spectrum between hydrogen and hydroxyl. Because it’s quiet and related to water, scientists think it’s a natural place for aliens to broadcast.";
"FactAlien83"                              = "The «Medusa Hypothesis» suggests that life itself occasionally creates conditions that lead to its own mass extinction. This could be why we don’t see many long-lived civilizations.";
"FactAlien84"                              = "NASA’s Kepler Space Telescope discovered that there are more planets than stars in our galaxy. Statistically, every star you see in the night sky likely has at least one planet.";
"FactAlien85"                              = "The James Webb Space Telescope can «sniff» the atmospheres of exoplanets by watching how starlight passes through them. It is our best tool yet for finding «bio-signatures» on distant worlds.";
"FactAlien86"                              = "«Super-Earths» (planets larger than Earth but smaller than Neptune) are the most common type of planet in the galaxy. Ironically, we don’t have a single one in our own solar system.";
"FactAlien87"                              = "Some believe that «Von Neumann Probes» — self-replicating robots — could map the entire galaxy in a few million years. If they existed, we should have seen them by now.";
"FactAlien88"                              = "The «Great Silence» refers to the fact that we have been listening for 60 years and haven’t heard a single confirmed word. Space is either very empty or we are very bad at listening.";
"FactAlien89"                              = "Chirality (the «handedness» of molecules) might be determined by the spin of cosmic rays. This could mean that life everywhere in a galaxy shares the same molecular «orientation».";
"FactAlien90"                              = "The «Habitable Edge» of an icy moon is the thin interface where the ice meets the ocean. This is where nutrients and energy are most likely to mix and spark life.";
"FactAlien91"                              = "If we found life on Mars, we would have to prove it wasn’t just «Earth life» we accidentally sent there. We’ve been crashing probes into Mars for decades, and some microbes may have survived.";
"FactAlien92"                              = "«Biological dark matter» refers to the 99% of microbes on Earth that cannot be grown in a lab. If we can’t understand the life here, understanding life on another planet will be incredibly difficult.";
"FactAlien93"                              = "The «Gaia Hypothesis» suggests that life and its environment form a single self-regulating system. An «alien» might not be a single creature, but an entire planetary organism.";
"FactAlien94"                              = "Some researchers look for «Megastructures» around White Dwarfs. Since these stars are dead, any large structure there would almost certainly be artificial.";
"FactAlien95"                              = "«Extraterrestrial» doesn’t always mean «from another planet». Life could theoretically exist in the atmosphere of a star or even in the vacuum of a nebula.";
"FactAlien96"                              = "The «Copernican Principle» states that Earth is not special. If we are typical, then the universe should be absolutely teeming with life just like us.";
"FactAlien97"                              = "«Tidal Heating» can keep a moon warm even if it’s far from the sun. The constant squeezing from a giant planet’s gravity creates friction and heat in the moon’s core.";
"FactAlien98"                              = "«Zombie Planets» are those that orbit pulsars (dead, spinning stars). These planets are bathed in lethal radiation, making life there almost impossible—but not quite.";
"FactAlien99"                              = "Symmetry (having a left and right side) is common on Earth because it helps with movement. Alien life might use radial symmetry (like a starfish) or no symmetry at all.";
"FactAlien100"                             = "Despite all the math and telescopes, the only «weird fact» we know for sure is that we exist. That alone is enough to prove that the universe is capable of producing life.";
